@Not my Fav - I have made this with both mature spinach and chard since I had both and we wanted to compare. It came out just fine with either and not overcooked. 
This is a recipe easy to scale up or down with great flavor, though we like sake best because we want to taste the salmon more than the wine. 
Definitely a good year round, easy supper. Maybe that's why we have choices -

@Rachel Scott. 
I am a retired internist and epidemiologist. What you heard from that expert seems out of date after a number of large trials. This is what the American Heart Association now recommends (from their website) : “Americans consume far too much sodium — on average, over 3,300 milligrams daily. The American Heart Association recommends no more than 2,300 mg a day and optimal goal of no more than 1,500 mg a day for most adults.  

For most people, cutting back by 1,000 mg a day can improve blood pressure and heart health.  “

@Peter Absolutely reminiscent of the Date Farm shakes. Those were the best! 
Sub vanilla ice cream for the buttermilk and that will take you right back to P.S.  
For a bit less sugar, I make this shake with oat milk instead of buttermilk and it is wonderful.

@linda bell I substituted maple syrup for corn syrup and it worked. 

My main note is that the nuts should be glazed all over, not just underneath. The nuts on the half of the cake prepared according to the directions were largely unremarkable, but on the other section of the cake I reserved half of the glaze so it was poured over AND under, the pecans, to wonderful candied nut effect.  

Otherwise, this recipe was not really a showstopper, but more of a 'master of none' combo.

@Gonzalo
You can use whatever pot or device you have.  Ideally the sauce pan with lid, the rice maker or the INSTAPOT are appropriate in size to the amount of rice you are making.  I was taught that a smaller batch of rice should not be cooked in a huge pot — something about needing a lot of steam and changing the timing and texture of the rice.  

When I use the INSTAPOT (6 quarts?) I make several extra servings to store in the freezer for later. When I had a small rice cooker, I used it to make entire  one pot meals.
